1
00:00:02,491 --> 00:00:05,382
<i> "Battle." "Fight."</i>

2
00:00:06,321 --> 00:00:09,407
<i>"Win." "Lose."</i>

3
00:00:10,150 --> 00:00:11,402
<i>These are the words we use</i>

4
00:00:11,487 --> 00:00:14,689
<i>when someone is diagnosed
with an illness or a disease.</i>

5
00:00:14,916 --> 00:00:19,636
♪ No wind, no rain ♪

6
00:00:19,862 --> 00:00:23,381
♪ Or winter's cold ♪

7
00:00:23,466 --> 00:00:26,462
♪ Can stop me, baby ♪

8
00:00:26,590 --> 00:00:28,874
♪ Oh, baby ♪

9
00:00:29,038 --> 00:00:32,118
♪ If you're my goal ♪

10
00:00:32,241 --> 00:00:36,376
♪ Ah, ah, ah, ah ♪

11
00:00:36,680 --> 00:00:38,495
<i>We use militarized language</i>

12
00:00:38,581 --> 00:00:40,498
<i>that implies
it's a fair fight.</i>

13
00:00:46,311 --> 00:00:48,595
- God grant me the serenity
- God grant me the serenity

14
00:00:48,758 --> 00:00:51,676
to accept the things
I cannot change,

15
00:00:51,761 --> 00:00:54,962
the courage to change
the things I can,

16
00:00:55,251 --> 00:00:57,212
and the wisdom
to know the difference.

17
00:00:57,328 --> 00:00:58,982
<i>But when it comes
to life and death,</i>

18
00:00:59,068 --> 00:01:01,103
<i>what does winning
really look like?</i>

19
00:01:01,559 --> 00:01:03,176
<i>Is a person a loser for dying</i>

20
00:01:03,262 --> 00:01:05,580
<i>when the outcome isn't really
in their control...</i>

21
00:01:05,775 --> 00:01:07,595
Oh. Damn it.

22
00:01:07,681 --> 00:01:09,093
If any patients
see you like that,

23
00:01:09,178 --> 00:01:10,595
they might go
to another hospital.

24
00:01:10,681 --> 00:01:11,698
Always gets me
in the mood.

25
00:01:11,783 --> 00:01:13,335
Plus, you know, I'm seeing
what daylight feels like

26
00:01:13,420 --> 00:01:14,501
while I still can.

27
00:01:14,876 --> 00:01:15,931
How's Catherine?

28
00:01:16,017 --> 00:01:17,032
She's ready.

29
00:01:17,118 --> 00:01:18,657
- And you?
- Shh, shh, shh, shh.

30
00:01:20,469 --> 00:01:21,923
Ah.

31
00:01:22,091 --> 00:01:24,658
Funny bone.
Not as easy as it looks.

32
00:01:26,626 --> 00:01:28,743
Okay, then.
I have real patients,

33
00:01:28,829 --> 00:01:31,376
so, you know,
good luck with... all this.

34
00:01:34,523 --> 00:01:35,868
I'm messing with you.

35
00:01:36,556 --> 00:01:39,357
You're gonna do great.
You and Amelia.

36
00:01:39,442 --> 00:01:41,559
You're ready.

37
00:01:41,644 --> 00:01:42,693
Charley horse.

38
00:01:50,235 --> 00:01:52,399
There he is.
Thought you might need this.

39
00:01:52,485 --> 00:01:54,798
Oh. No, thanks.
But I'm... I'm good.

40
00:01:54,884 --> 00:01:56,574
I'm running late
for Catherine's scans.

41
00:01:56,659 --> 00:01:58,393
Okay, well, I have cleared
all my surgeries today

42
00:01:58,478 --> 00:01:59,454
and shored up child care,

43
00:01:59,540 --> 00:02:00,713
so I'm here for you,
whatever you need,

44
00:02:00,798 --> 00:02:02,962
- whenever you need it.
- Like I said, I'm good.

45
00:02:03,493 --> 00:02:06,048
Okay, Richard,
it's gonna be a very long day.

46
00:02:06,150 --> 00:02:09,387
Look, Meredith,
I have plenty of doctors

47
00:02:09,472 --> 00:02:11,368
and plenty of friends
looking out for me.

48
00:02:11,571 --> 00:02:14,243
You know who doesn't?
Your father.

49
00:02:14,859 --> 00:02:17,243
Molly had to get back to Bahrain
with her kids.

50
00:02:17,329 --> 00:02:18,407
He's all alone.

51
00:02:18,493 --> 00:02:20,665
And I will make time
to see Thatcher this week,

52
00:02:20,751 --> 00:02:22,743
but today is all
about you and Catherine.

53
00:02:22,844 --> 00:02:24,665
Meredith, Thatcher may not
have a week.

54
00:02:25,634 --> 00:02:27,900
Now, I know it's never been easy
between you two,

55
00:02:28,086 --> 00:02:30,203
but the time to change that
is running out.

56
00:02:31,814 --> 00:02:33,189
Excuse me.

